Barratt, BG Group, BP, Shell, Tesco: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 
2011-09-16T06:49:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-15/bp-plc-international-power-shell-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and
Irish markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last market close.  Futures on the benchmark FTSE 100 Index gained 0.7 percent
to 5,380 at 7:48 a.m. in London. The FTSE 100 advanced 110.52
points, or 2.1 percent, to 5,337.54 yesterday. The FTSE All-
Share Index rose 2.1 percent to 2,766.46, while Ireland’s ISEQ
Index declined 0.2 percent to 2,463.88.  Barratt Developments Plc (BDEV)  : The company’s group
finance director,  David Thomas , bought 25,000 shares at 79.55
apiece on Sept. 15. The stock jumped 5.3 percent to 81.05 pence.  BG Group Plc (BG/)  : The oil producer has held talks with
at least one Chinese oil company interested in the U.K. energy
group’s Brazilian business, the Financial Times reported, citing
unnamed people familiar with the matter. The shares increased
2.2 percent to 1,262 pence.  BP Plc (BP/)  : Europe’s second-largest oil company,
Transocean Ltd. and Halliburton Co. will get U.S. violation
notices for the Gulf of Mexico oil spill, said Michael Bromwich,
director of the Bureau of Ocean Energy Management, Regulation
and Enforcement. The shares jumped 4 percent to 411 pence.  International Power Plc (IPR)  : The U.K. utility
controlled by GDF Suez SA said it has no plans to invest in
Chinese power generation. The shares climbed 2.1 percent to
333.3 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s largest oil
company has renewed its agreement with Gabon allowing it to
operate in the country until 2028, according to an Oil Ministry
report. The stock gained 3.3 percent to 2,100 pence.  Tesco Plc (TSCO)  : The U.K.’s largest retailer aims to
open as many as 25 stores a year in China to “keep pace” with
the nation’s growth, said David Potts, its head of Asian
operations. The shares increased 1.4 percent to 370.95 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
